<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-12-03T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-12-03T11:00:00-05:00" n="439" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d439">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">852.75 National Telephone Company/71:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain (<persName type="from">Laughlin</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Madrid</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-12-03T16:00:00+00:00">December 3, 1932—4
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 3—1:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>101. <persName corresp="#p_RCLN1">Rock</persName> is informed by a
                                source close to Government that if the American press were
                                immediately to launch a rumor that I be at once withdrawn thus
                                provoking a state of “semi-diplomatic rupture” in the event that
                                Spain maintained an <hi rend="italic">intransigeant</hi> attitude
                                the peseta might react to such a statement thereby exercising an
                                important and essential influence on the Spanish position.</p>
                            <closer><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">Laughlin</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>